item.title: China Releases Australian Journalist Detained on Suspicion of Disclosing State Secrets
item.description: The release of Cheng Lei, who had been detained for more than three years, removes a key irritant in a tense relationship between the two countries.

item.title: Country Garden Services' President Resigns
item.description: Country Garden Services Holdings’ Li Changjiang has resigned as its president, executive director and authorized representative amid an escalating crisis in China’s property sector.

item.title: Oil Prices Tick Higher on Concerns Over Israel Conflict
item.description: Oil prices ticked higher, putting prices broadly where they were from the rally at the start of the week, as worries that the situation in Israel could spill over into other countries supported markets.

item.title: Metals Rise as Dollar Eases
item.description: Base metals and gold prices were higher in early London trading, with a falling dollar helping support commodities backed by the greenback.

item.title: Dollar Could Get a Lift From Fed Minutes, Inflation Data
item.description: The dollar has sagged after recent comments from Fed officials suggesting that rates are unlikely to rise further, but it might get a lift when Fed minutes are released, as well as inflation data on Thursday, XS.com said.

item.title: What Is Hamas? What to Know About the Militant Group Fighting Israel
item.description: Hamas upended the stability of the entire Middle East when its fighters surged into Israel from the Gaza Strip. What exactly are its objectives?

item.title: Bang & Olufsen Backs Views After Earnings Beat Hopes
item.description: Bang & Olufsen posted better-than-expected first-quarter earnings as profits benefited from price increases and the sale of more higher-margin products, while supply-chain and logistic costs normalized.

item.title: German Inflation Drops to Lowest Level Since Start of Ukraine War
item.description: German consumer prices were 4.5% higher in September, confirming prior estimates and hitting its lowest rate since the outbreak of the war in Ukraine, a level the ECB could consider enough to end its current hiking cycle.

item.title: German Bund Auction a Test of Demand for Cheap Extra-Long Debt
item.description: Germany’s €2.5 billion auction of 2048- and 2052-dated Bunds will be an opportunity to gauge demand for ultra-long debt after a recent rise in yields in this segment, UniCredit Research said.

item.title: Nikkei Rises 0.6%, Led by Auto, Chip Stocks
item.description: The Nikkei Stock Average ended 0.6% higher at 31936.51 as gains in auto and chip stocks helped offset losses in financial and shipping shares.

item.title: How Hamas Turned an Israeli Music Festival Into a Massacre
item.description: A festival in southern Israel became one of the deadliest sites of Hamas’s surprise attack on Israel, with more than 250 casualties. We break down how the attack unfolded.

item.title: IMAX China Falls After Buyout Is Voted Down
item.description: IMAX China Holding shares were volatile after shareholders rejected a $124 million buyout proposal, ensuring shares will remain listed in Hong Kong.

item.title: Tough Market, Not Leadership Changes, Weighed on BOQ Earnings, CEO Says
item.description: Bank of Queensland’s disappointing earnings and lending margins were affected by challenging economic conditions rather than management changes that unsettled some analysts.

item.title: Battleground Ukraine: Shifting Strategies and a Potential Stalemate
item.description: Retired Brigadier Gen. Mark Kimmit and WSJ Ukraine correspondent James Marson explain Ukraine’s evolving counteroffensive military strategy and what could be next for Europe’s biggest land war since World War II.

item.title: Australia's Plan to Address Colonial Legacy Divides Those It Aims to Help
item.description: A referendum on amending the country’s constitution to recognize indigenous people is proving controversial.

item.title: U.S. stocks rose, with the S&P 500, Nasdaq and Dow gaining 0.5%, 0.6% and 0.4%, respectively. The 10-year Treasury yield settled at 4.654%, down from 4.783% on Friday.

item.title: Winter Is Coming, and Southwest Swears This Time It Will Be Ready
item.description: We went to summer deicing school to see how the airline plans to keep travelers moving through messy weather.
